SIMPLE: indication
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Indication
<hw>In`di*ca"tion</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[L.
<ets>indicatio</ets>: cf. F. <ets>indication</ets>.]</ety>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <def>Act of pointing out or indicating.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>That which serves to indicate or point out; mark;
token; sign; symptom; evidence.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The frequent stops they make in the most convenient places are
plain <qex>indications</qex> of their weariness.</q>
<rj><qau>Addison.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>Discovery made; information.</def>
<rj><au>Bentley.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>Explanation; display.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>
<rj><au>Bacon.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <fld>(Med.)</fld> <def>Any symptom or occurrence in a
disease, which serves to direct to suitable remedies. Opposite of
<ant>contraindication</ant>.</def></p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- Proof; demonstration; sign; token; mark;
evidence; signal.</syn>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Indicative</ent>⟦br⟧
